This spontaneous report was received from a consumer or other non health professional (patient's father) and 
concerns a 4-year-old male patient from the United States: 017462380A.
The patient's height was not reported and his weight was 39 pounds. The patient's medical history and concurrent 
conditions included: shots
The patient was treated with paracetamol (suspension, oral) 12.5 ml (7.5 mL out of his dosing cup and 5 mL of his 
brothers) initiated on 07-JAN-2016 for pain relief. Concomitant medications were not reported.
On 07-JAN-2016, the consumer (patient's father) reported that his son accidentally took 2 doses of CHILDREN'S 
CHERRY TYLENOL. He was 39 pounds and took his 7.5 mL out of his dosing cup and then took 5 mL of his 
brothers who weighs 35 pounds (accidentally administered extra dose). The reporter stated that he had measured 
out in 2 different dosing cups at their grandmother's house for them to take for pain relief after having shots 
yesterday (day before report). It was not the first time the patient used TYLENOL. The patient was still using 
TYLENOL CHILDREN'S CHERRY liquid for pain relief as told by doctor. The doctor was not aware that the patient 
accidentally drank both dosing cup.
Action taken with paracetamol was not applicable.
The outcome for accidentally administered extra dose was not reported.
This report was not serious.